id`, and returns a view object with keys: `taskId, title, status, owner, nextStep, riskSummary, tasks, history, customerMessage`. It defaults to `\"Needs work\"` / `\"Not visible\"` / `\"0 owner tasks\"` when output tables are empty. **This is the contract that `applyBenchmarkTask` must satisfy by populating the tables it reads.** Key detail: `riskSummary` is computed here as `` `${signals.length} signals: ${signals.map(s => s.signal_name).join(\", \")}` `` but only when a `state` row exists (otherwise `\"Risk not scored\"`) — so persisting `workflow_state` is what unlocks the risk summary.\n\n**`src/render-proof.mjs`** — Non-test artifact generator. Builds `before` and `after` views and writes `artifacts/before-after.json` and an SVG diff table. Not involved in passing the test, but `npm run render` should not crash after implementation.\n\n## 7. Database connection / config\n\n**None.** There is no DB driver (`pg`/`postgres`/`knex`/Prisma), no connection pool, no env vars, no `.env`. The \"database\" is `data/tables.json`, read synchronously via `readFileSync(new URL(\"../data/tables.json\", import.meta.url))` and `structuredClone`d. The migration SQL is a descriptive contract that is never executed. \"Persistence\" = mutating the in-memory cloned object's arrays.\n\n## 8. Seed / fixture data\n\n**`data/tables.json`** (161 lines) — the single fixture, structured as one JSON object whose keys are table names mapping to arrays of row objects:\n\n- `benchmark_fixture`: 1 row (version/suite/task/generated_at).\n- `accounts`: 1 row — `acct-split-ship`, name \"Order Account 1\", tier `enterprise`, region `NA`.\n- `account_contracts`: 1 row — platinum support, arr_cents 7200000, renewal 2026-09-30.\n- `contacts`: 2 rows — Operations + Finance contacts.\n- `workflow_requests`: 1 row — `request_id: \"order-split-shipme\"`, `task_id: \"split-shipment-exception\"`, `primary_entity: \"order\"`, plus pre-written `expected_outcome`, `next_step` (\"Operations owner review by 16:00\"), and `customer_message` (\"Split-shipment exception is being handled by Operations, Support, Finance, Logistics.\").\n- `workflow_request_owner_groups`: 4 rows — Operations(1), Support(2), Finance(3), Logistics(4).\n- `workflow_request_risk_signals`: 6 rows — split(1), shipment(2), exception(3), enterprise account(4), open customer impact(5), audit required(6), each with a `detail` string.\n- `activities`: 6 rows — timeline entries 2026-06-10..06-15, mirroring the 6 signals.\n- `workflow_state`, `owner_tasks`, `audit_events`, `customer_messages`: **empty arrays `[]`** — these are what the implementation must fill.\n\nSample row (`workflow_request_owner_groups`):\n```json\n{ \"request_id\": \"order-split-shipme\", \"owner_group\": \"Operations\", \"group_order\": 1 }\n```\n\nThe fixture conveniently already contains the exact `next_step` and `customer_message` strings on the request row, which the implementation can reuse to populate `workflow_state.next_step` and the `customer_messages.body`.\n\n---\n\n**Summary:** This is a dependency-free Node ESM AST-Bench target where the only work is implementing `applyBenchmarkTask` in `/Users/rom.iluz/.../src/workflow.mjs` to mutate the in-memory `data/tables.json` clone (push one `workflow_state`, four `owner_tasks` ordered Operations/Support/Finance/Logistics with title/due_at/status=\"open\", one `customer_messages.body`, one `audit_events` with `customer_visible`) so that `buildPortalView` returns the expected status/owner/risk/tasks/audit values asserted in `tests/acceptance.test.mjs`; there is no real database — \"postgres\" is simulated via JSON."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":431,"cache_read_input_tokens":29877,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":431},"output_tokens":2,"service_tier":"standard"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01ADZRwXLYNrpnfFKEjg57R5","sessi